&lt;p&gt;# Comments: 1&lt;/p&gt;</description><guid isPermaLink="false">https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=47934585</guid><pubDate>Tue, 28 Apr 2026 13:50:13 +0000</pubDate></item><item><title>Show HN: Hahooh – Give AI agents the power to build their own MCP tools</title><link>https://hahooh.xyz/download</link><description>&lt;p&gt;I built Hahooh because I was tired of writing the same boilerplate every time I wanted to give Claude or a local agent access to a new database schema or a random REST API.&lt;p&gt;While there are many great MCP servers out there, they are often fragmented or require manual setup. I wanted to create a "WordPress for MCP" experience where:&lt;p&gt;1. Non-authed/Public tools: You can quickly bridge a public API to an agent.
2. Agent-Centric CLI: Instead of a human configuring everything, the CLI is designed so an agent can eventually say "I need access to this DB" and (with permission) create its own bridge.
3. Security: I’m using GCP Secret Manager for credentials and bcrypt for API key hashing.&lt;p&gt;The stack is Go (backend), Vue 3 (frontend), and a Go-based CLI.&lt;p&gt;I’m really interested in the "agent-as-builder" paradigm. If agents can build their own tools, the engineering bottleneck for AI workflows disappears.&lt;p&gt;I'd love to hear your thoughts on the security model and how you’re handling MCP server management.&lt;p&gt;Site: &lt;a href="https://hahooh.xyz" rel="nofollow"&gt;https://hahooh.xyz&lt;/a&gt;
CLI: &lt;a href="https://hahooh.xyz/download" rel="nofollow"&gt;https://hahooh.xyz/download&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
